        <!-- Section 1: The Challenges -->
        <section id="challenges" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-4">The Old Way: A Broken System</h2>
            <p class="text-lg text-stone-700 text-center max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-12">
                Traditional data architectures forced teams into compromises. They were split between two separate, complex systems: the Data Warehouse (DW) and the Data Lake (DL). This created data silos, increased costs, and made it nearly impossible to implement modern AI.
            </p>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-amber-700">Proprietary & Costly</h3>
                    <p class="text-stone-600">
                        Data Warehouses use proprietary data formats. This leads to high costs and "vendor lock-in," making it difficult and expensive to move your data or use other tools.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-amber-700">Data Silos & Complexity</h3>
                    <p class="text-stone-600">
                        BI teams used the DW, while AI teams used the DL. This required constant, complex ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) pipelines just to move data, creating duplicates and governance nightmares.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-amber-700">Poor Quality & Governance</h3>
                    <p class="text-stone-600">
                        Data Lakes, while flexible, lacked critical features like schema enforcement and transactions. This led to unreliable data ("data swamps") unfit for BI or mission-critical AI.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: The Solution -->
        <section id="solution" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
